Sure! Here is the simplest possible way to run WordPress + MySQL using Docker Compose ‚Äî very easy, just copy‚Äìpaste and run.

This is the cleanest, beginner-friendly, and 100% working method.

‚≠ê STEP 1 ‚Äî Create a folder

Open PowerShell:

mkdir wordpress-db
cd wordpress-db

‚≠ê STEP 2 ‚Äî Create a docker-compose.yml file

Inside the folder create a file named:

docker-compose.yml


Paste this simple WordPress + MySQL setup:

services:
  db:
    image: mysql:5.7
    environment:
      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root
      MYSQL_DATABASE: wordpress
    volumes:
      - db_data:/var/lib/mysql

  wordpress:
    image: wordpress:latest
    ports:
      - "8080:80"
    environment:
      WORDPRESS_DB_HOST: db
      WORDPRESS_DB_USER: root
      WORDPRESS_DB_PASSWORD: root
      WORDPRESS_DB_NAME: wordpress
    depends_on:
      - db

volumes:
  db_data:

‚úî What this does:

Creates a MySQL DB container

Creates a WordPress container

Connects them together

Saves database permanently

Exposes WordPress at http://localhost:8080

‚≠ê STEP 3 ‚Äî Start both containers

Run this:

docker compose up -d


(or docker-compose up -d in older Docker)

This will:

Download MySQL

Download WordPress

Start both

Link them automatically

‚≠ê STEP 4 ‚Äî Open WordPress

Open:

http://localhost:8080


You will see the WordPress setup page.
Choose language ‚Üí set site name ‚Üí create admin user.

That‚Äôs it.

‚≠ê STEP 5 ‚Äî Stop the containers (when needed)
docker compose down


If you also want to delete database data:

docker compose down -v

